	<item>
		<title>Does Trendjacking Work? Dos, Don&#8217;ts &#038; Examples</title>
		<link>https://www.wordstream.com/blog/trendjacking</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Amanda Rodhe]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Mon, 13 Oct 2025 14:52:33 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Marketing Ideas]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://www.wordstream.com/?p=94880</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[<p>Trendjacking is a great way to gain attention. Here's how to do it safely.</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/trendjacking">Does Trendjacking Work? Dos, Don&#8217;ts &#038; Examples</a> appeared first on <a href="https://www.wordstream.com">WordStream</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>On average, YouTubers upload <a href="https://blog.youtube/press/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">20 million</a> videos each day, while Instagram users place <a href="https://localiq.com/blog/what-happens-in-an-internet-minute/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">66,000 visuals</a>¬†on that platform every minute.</p>
<p>A vast majority of that content slips by with little fanfare. But every once in a while, something breaks through the barrage of vacation photos and dance clips to go absolutely viral. You know some of them well: the mannequin challenge, sea shanties, ‚ÄúThis Barbie is‚Ä¶‚Äù</p>
<p>Cultural moments like these hit the algorithm just right, ricochet across the globe, and leave people rushing to get in on the trend.</p>
<p>Brands can tap into these events‚Äîa tactic called trendjacking‚Äî to capture the attention of new people and expand their circle of influence at an incredible scale. But not all viral trends are created equal. Some can damage your brand just as quickly.</p>
<p>Let‚Äôs dig into the phenomenon of trendjacking, how to leverage it for business growth, and when it‚Äôs best to proceed with caution.</p>
<h3>Contents</h3>
<ul>
<li><a href="#what-is-trendjacking">What is trendjacking?</a></li>
<li><a href="#why-try-trendjacking">Is trendjacking right for you?</a></li>
<li><a href="#trendjacking-dos-and-donts">Trendjacking dos and don‚Äôts (with examples)</a></li>
</ul>
<div id="what-is-trendjacking"></div>
<h2>What is trendjacking?</h2>
<p>Trendjacking is the act of capitalizing on a viral cultural moment. And the practice can take several forms. If your brand‚Ä¶</p>
<ul>
<li>Reshares a trending meme (Think: ‚ÄúOne does not simply‚Ä¶‚Äù)</li>
<li>Taps your team to recreate a viral dance or performance challenge (Think: Gangnam Style)</li>
<li>Participates in a challenge for charity (Think: the Ice Bucket Challenge)</li>
<li>Creates its own version of a trending GPT image (Think: the Studio Ghibli image trend)</li>
<li>Shares <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/fall-content-ideas">content</a> related to a trending phrase (Think: ‚ÄúVery demure, very mindful‚Äù)</li>
</ul>
<p>‚Ä¶or otherwise creates content that is based on an ‚Äúof the moment‚Äù internet craze, congratulations, you‚Äôre trendjacking.</p>
<p><img fetchpriority="high" decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/trendjacking-wordstream-pilates.webp" alt="Trendjacking - Pilates stucio sign." width="937" height="566" class="aligncenter wp-image-94882 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/trendjacking-wordstream-pilates.webp 937w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/trendjacking-wordstream-pilates-480x290.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 937px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://www.instagram.com/p/C_vcv79O9SJ/?utm_source=ig_web_copy_link&amp;igsh=cTB1emNxd3l1YmY3" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Source</em></a></p>
<p>You may also try your hand at trendjacking‚Äôs close cousin, newsjacking.</p>
<p>While trendjacking trades in cultural cachet, newsjacking is the art of engaging with a viral news moment. Of course, there‚Äôs a bit of a gray area between the two tactics. For example, commenting on the Sydney Sweeney ‚Äúgood jeans/genes‚Äù ad campaign is a bit of both. But the crucial component in either practice is the timeliness of the content and commentary.</p>
<p><img src="https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/16.0.1/72x72/1f6a8.png" alt="üö®" class="wp-smiley" style="height: 1em; max-height: 1em;" /> <strong>How do you turn attention into traffic?</strong> Download <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/resources/increase-traffic-to-your-website?cid=Web_Any_BlogInContent_PPC_25WaysIncreaseTraffic_Download">25 Ways to Increase Traffic to Your Website</a> to find out!</p>
<div id="why-try-trendjacking"></div>
<h2>Is trendjacking right for your business?</h2>
<p>On the internet, attention is currency. So, finding creative ways to draw attention to your brand can pay dividends. That‚Äôs why many brands want to work trendjacking into their <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/social-media-strategy">social media strategy</a>.</p>
<p>Done right, trendjacking can help you:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Get greater reach without creating your own virality: </strong>You ride the wave of a broader cultural moment.</li>
<li><strong>Prove your cultural <em>bona fides</em>: </strong>Businesses in trend-based industries (fashion, beauty, wellness, etc.) get bonus points for cultural fluency. Engaging with a viral fad signals you know what‚Äôs up.</li>
<li><strong>Show off your personality: </strong>Tap into a trend that has a cheeky link to your brand, and you prove your wit. Few things <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2021/09/23/how-brand-your-business">make a brand more attractive</a> than a good sense of humor.</li>
<li><strong>Drive traffic:</strong> If your contribution to the trend takes off, you boost traffic to your social pages and website. Hello, new group of <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/hot-leads-vs-cold-leads">leads to nurture</a>!</li>
<li><strong>Build </strong><a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2015/07/10/brand-awareness"><strong>brand awareness</strong></a>: Even if those new followers aren‚Äôt ready to buy, it‚Äôs never bad to have more eyeballs on your brand. They might buy from you in six months, or their friends might want to buy today.</li>
</ul>
<div id="trendjacking-dos-and-donts"></div>
<h2>8 trendjacking dos and don‚Äôts (with examples)</h2>
<p>Just because trendjacking can produce wins for your brand doesn‚Äôt mean it‚Äôs always the right choice.</p>
<p>Some trends are too risqu√© for a brand to take a chance on. Others simply aren‚Äôt the right fit for <em>your</em> brand. And some businesses aren‚Äôt positioned to move quickly enough to make the most of a viral moment.</p>
<p>If you‚Äôve sat on the sidelines before or you‚Äôve gotten involved without much success, these dos and don‚Äôts can help you assess future trendjacking opportunities and leverage them more effectively.</p>
<h3>Trendjacking dos</h3>
<p>Want to get better at identifying worthy trendjacking moments and capitalizing on the ones with real promise? Start here.</p>
<h4>1. Do target trends relevant to your industry</h4>
<p>When you see a trend and think you might want to participate, start by asking yourself, ‚ÄúDoes this make sense with my brand‚Äôs focus?‚Äù If the answer is yes, you can proceed to further evaluation. If the answer is no, save yourself some time and stop right here.</p>
<p>Not sure what this looks like in practice? Let‚Äôs explore the question for some hypothetical brands using the <a href="https://time.com/5929245/sea-shanty-tiktok-2021/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">sea shanty trend</a> as an example.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/trendjacking-wordstream-shanty.webp" alt="Trendjacking - sea shanty video still." width="365" height="600" class="aligncenter wp-image-94883 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/trendjacking-wordstream-shanty.webp 365w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/trendjacking-wordstream-shanty-183x300.webp 183w" sizes="(max-width: 365px) 100vw, 365px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UgsurPg9Ckw" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Source</em></a></p>
<p>In early 2021, COVID was still restricting our lives significantly. Perhaps because being trapped at home for 11 months straight felt a little like taking a long journey across the ocean, a 19th-century sea shanty went completely <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2023/12/14/tiktok-trend-discovery">viral on TikTok</a>. What started as duets on the original video soon blossomed into sea shanty versions of contemporary songs. (Smash Mouth‚Äôs All Star <a href="https://x.com/JennaGuillaume/status/1349241560936812544?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw%7Ctwcamp%5Etweetembed%7Ctwterm%5E1349241560936812544%7Ctwgr%5E%7Ctwcon%5Es1_&amp;ref_url=https%3A%2F%2Ftime.com%2F5929245%2Fsea-shanty-tiktok-2021%2F" target="_blank" rel="noopener">as a sea shanty</a>? Yes, that really happened.)</p>
<p>Imagine you‚Äôre leading marketing for your business at this time. You see the sea shanty trend taking off and think to yourself, ‚ÄúShould we get in on this?‚Äù</p>
<p><em>Scenario 1: </em>You run a local CPA firm. Your brand has nothing to do with the ocean. You do not need to get involved in the sea shanty trend.</p>
<p><em>Scenario 2: </em>You operate a restaurant with seafood on the menu. Sure, you can consider this trend. (This example was inspired by Arby‚Äôs, which found success creating <a href="https://www.tiktok.com/@arbys/video/6920243667865226501?lang=en" target="_blank" rel="noopener">a sea shanty TikTok</a> about its fish sandwich.)</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/trendjacking-wordstream-wendys-2.webp" alt="Trendjacking - Arby's video still." width="508" height="600" class="aligncenter wp-image-94884 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/trendjacking-wordstream-wendys-2.webp 508w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/trendjacking-wordstream-wendys-2-480x567.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 508px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://www.tiktok.com/@arbys/video/6920243667865226501?lang=en" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Source</em></a></p>
<h4>2. Do ask if this trend matters to your target audience</h4>
<p>Once you‚Äôve assessed a trend‚Äôs relevance for your industry, go a little deeper. Will your <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/05/11/target-audience">target audience</a> care if you post something about it?</p>
<p>Think about your audience‚Äôs demographics, psychographics, and general demeanor. Will they get the reference? And if they understand it, will they care that you‚Äôre engaging with it?</p>
<p>To continue with the sea shanty example, Arby‚Äôs passed this test, too. Its target audience, according to <a href="https://www.qsrweb.com/articles/arbys-redefines-target-audience-after-year-long-review/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">an interview</a> with its VP of brand and corporate communications, is younger consumers (aged 18-34) who ‚Äúlove to have fun.‚Äù</p>
<p>An irreverent, purposefully cringe TikTok video? That‚Äôs a perfect fit for this audience.</p>
<p><img src="https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/16.0.1/72x72/1f44b.png" alt="üëã" class="wp-smiley" style="height: 1em; max-height: 1em;" /> <strong>Free resource!</strong> <a href="https://marketing.localiq.com/WSLIQContentDLWebsiteTargetAudience.html?cid=Web_WS_InContent_Guide_TargetAudineceGuide_Download&amp;itm_source=wordstream&amp;itm_medium=blog&amp;itm_campaign=incontent_links">How to Find Your Target Audience in 6 Steps</a></p>
<h4>3. Do use related hashtags</h4>
<p>Trendjacking is all about capitalizing on a viral moment to expand your reach. Adding relevant <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2019/05/29/instagram-hashtags">hashtags</a> to your content can boost your distribution and position your brand alongside fellow trendjackers.</p>
<p>On its fish sandwich video, Arby‚Äôs added some strategic hashtags employed on other trending sea shanty videos.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/trendjacking-wordstream-wendys-1.webp" alt="Trendjacking -Arby's video with hashtags." width="587" height="600" class="aligncenter wp-image-94885 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/trendjacking-wordstream-wendys-1.webp 587w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/trendjacking-wordstream-wendys-1-480x491.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 587px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://www.tiktok.com/@arbys/video/6920243667865226501?lang=en" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Source</em></a></p>
<h4>4. Do be creative</h4>
<p>A viral trend goes stale quickly because it is, by definition, repetitive. There are only so many sea shanty videos a TikToker can watch before their eyes glaze over.</p>
<p>That‚Äôs why creativity is essential for brands trying trendjacking. What unique spin can you put on the trend, and how can it help your content stand out from the others?</p>
<p>This is also an opportunity to show off your <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2021/03/31/brand-personality-messaging">brand‚Äôs personality</a>. Don‚Äôt be afraid to take a creative risk within the framework of the trend.</p>
<h3>Trendjacking don‚Äôts</h3>
<p>If you‚Äôve tried trendjacking in the past with little success, these don‚Äôts might be holding you back. Avoid these common mistakes to get further with your viral-inspired content.</p>
<h4>5. Don‚Äôt chase bad trends</h4>
<p>Some trends aren‚Äôt a good fit for your brand. But other trends aren‚Äôt a good fit for <em>any</em> brand. Avoid these types of trends at all costs:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Mean or offensive trends: </strong>Consumers don‚Äôt like brands that punch down or are unnecessarily crass. If getting in on the trend means being petty or gross, don‚Äôt do it. <em>*The exception here is brands with an edgy voice. Adult Swim, you can participate!</em></li>
<li><strong>Confusing trends: </strong>If your marketing team doesn‚Äôt understand the trend, don‚Äôt do it. That means the trend is either: 1) Inscrutable to everyone (in which case, why bother?), or 2) Potentially hazardous. You may be missing a nefarious meaning that resonates on some dark side of the web.</li>
<li><strong>Hollow trends: </strong>This one can be hard to gauge‚Äîwho‚Äôd have thought we‚Äôd all still know <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mannequin_Challenge" target="_blank" rel="noopener">the mannequin challenge</a> nearly a decade later? But if a trend feels particularly vapid or fleeting, take a pass.</li>
</ul>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/trendjacking-wordstream-digiorno.webp" alt="Trendjacking -DiGiornos Tweet." width="937" height="335" class="aligncenter wp-image-94886 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/trendjacking-wordstream-digiorno.webp 937w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/trendjacking-wordstream-digiorno-480x172.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 937px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://www.prnewsonline.com/whyistayed-twitter-campaign-backfires-on-digiornos-pizza/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>DiGiorno</em></a><em> had to eat its words after jumping on the wrong viral trend.</em></p>
<h4>6. Don‚Äôt trendjack too often</h4>
<p>Chasing every last trend is exhausting for your team. You have limited bandwidth, so think carefully before leaping at a trendjacking opportunity.</p>
<p>Not only that, if your brand participates too regularly in viral moments, you become a one-trick pony. Give your team the breathing room to create meaningful content and your audience the space to be surprised and delighted when you <em>do</em> engage in a trend.</p>
<h4>7. Don‚Äôt take forever to post</h4>
<p>Viral trends move fast. A new meme, GIF, or challenge may only last a week or so before it reaches peak saturation and completely sputters out. If you think of trendjacking as existing on a bell curve, you want to get your content out before the peak.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/trendjacking-wordstream-graph.webp" alt="Trendjacking - Bell curve of popularity." width="937" height="530" class="aligncenter wp-image-94887 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/trendjacking-wordstream-graph.webp 937w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/trendjacking-wordstream-graph-480x272.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 937px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>If your internal approval process means it will take weeks to get your trendjacking content published, sit this one out.</p>
<p>And if you work in a highly regulated industry where compliance and legal often need to opine on your marketing output, create a fast-track approval process for trend-related posts in advance. Then, when the right trend comes along, you‚Äôve already created a pathway for your team to get content out quickly.</p>
<h4>8. Don‚Äôt assume success</h4>
<p>As you try trendjacking, always keep track of your content‚Äôs results. Which trendjacking posts move the needle for your brand in meaningful ways (reshares, new follows, great consumer feedback, media mentions), and which fall flat?</p>
<p>As you continue to play with trendjacking, you‚Äôll see patterns emerge. Identifying the elements of a trending moment that resonate with your audience can help you further refine your trendjacking strategy and drive greater social media success.</p>
<h2>Try trendjacking for a big boost in brand awareness</h2>
<p>When done successfully, trendjacking is a proven tactic for gaining a ton of attention, especially on social media.</p>
<p>As you think through your first trend hijacking adventure, remember these dos and don‚Äôts:</p>
<ul>
<li>Do target trends relevant to your industry</li>
<li>Do ask if this trend matters to your target audience</li>
<li>Do use relatable hashtags</li>
<li>Do be creative</li>
<li>Don‚Äôt chase bad trends</li>
<li>Don‚Äôt trendjack too often</li>
<li>Don‚Äôt take forever to post</li>
<li>Don‚Äôt assume success</li>
</ul>
<p>The post <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/trendjacking">Does Trendjacking Work? Dos, Don&#8217;ts &#038; Examples</a> appeared first on <a href="https://www.wordstream.com">WordStream</a>.</p>
