		<title>7 Easy Ways to Lower Cost Per Lead Fast</title>
		<link>https://www.wordstream.com/blog/how-to-lower-cost-per-lead</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Amanda Rodhe]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Wed, 04 Sep 2024 12:00:33 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Reporting & Analysis]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://www.wordstream.com/?p=85495</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[<p>Want to lower your cost per lead? Try these seven actionable tips.</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/how-to-lower-cost-per-lead">7 Easy Ways to Lower Cost Per Lead Fast</a> appeared first on <a href="https://www.wordstream.com">WordStream</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Cost per lead (CPL) is a significant metric in digital advertising. For pay-per-click (PPC) and social media campaigns, businesses monitor CPL to understand whether their marketing efforts (and associated costs) are worth it.</p>
<p>The more expensive it is to acquire a lead, the less gross profit you‚Äôll expect to see in the long run, as lead acquisition costs eat into your earnings. Marketers and advertisers want to find the sweet spot between investing in getting the word out about their company and ensuring those efforts are as efficient as possible in converting new prospects into leads.</p>
<p>So, we put together this complete cost-per-lead guide to help with that. We&#8217;ll walk through how you can calculate and lower your cost per lead in a flash.</p>
<h3>Contents</h3>
<ul>
<li><a href="#how-to-calculate-cost-per-lead">How to calculate cost per lead</a></li>
<li><a href="#how-to-lower-cost-per-lead">How to lower your cost per lead</a></li>
<li><a href="#lower-cost-per-lead">Next steps: take action on these cost-per-lead tactics</a></li>
</ul>
<div id="how-to-calculate-cost-per-lead"></div>
<h2>How do you calculate cost per lead?</h2>
<p>To identify the best ways to lower CPL, it first helps to understand how it‚Äôs calculated. The cost-per-lead formula is pretty simple.</p>
<p>Total cost / total number of conversions = CPL</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/09/how-to-calculate-cost-per-lead.webp" alt="cost per lead formula" width="935" height="392" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-85496" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/09/how-to-calculate-cost-per-lead.webp 935w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/09/how-to-calculate-cost-per-lead-480x201.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 935px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>So, if you want to lower your CPL, you have two options: aim to generate more conversions while holding your spending steady or decrease your spending while maintaining your number of conversions.</p>
<p><img src="https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/16.0.1/72x72/26a1.png" alt="‚ö°" class="wp-smiley" style="height: 1em; max-height: 1em;" /> <strong>Get more leads fast using our free<a href="https://marketing.localiq.com/WSLIQContentDL25LeadGenIdeas.html?cid=Web_WS_InContent_Guide_LeadGenIdeas_Download" target="_blank" rel="noopener">¬†Definitive Guide to Lead Generation</a></strong> complete with over 25 tips, ideas, and examples!</p>
<div id="how-to-lower-cost-per-lead"></div>
<h2>How to lower cost per lead: 7 tips</h2>
<p>Here are seven ways to lower your cost per lead over time.</p>
<h3>1. Take stock of your current performance metrics</h3>
<p>The first step in finding ways to lower CPL is learning where you stand today. Crunch the numbers for each marketing or advertising campaign you have underway. This will allow you to identify any weak spots quickly. Is there a particular campaign that‚Äôs quite costly but not generating many leads? It might be time to forgo that pursuit.</p>
<p>On the flip side, you can ferret out opportunities for improvement. If you have a <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2020/12/09/free-and-low-budget-marketing-ideas" target="_blank" rel="noopener">low-cost marketing tactic</a> that generates quite a few leads already, can you optimize it further to attract even more leads?</p>
<p>During this process, you might wonder if your CPL is good. It‚Äôs a fair question! Any CPL greater than the cost of your product or service is too high. It can also be helpful to measure yourself against competitors by checking out <a href="https://localiq.com/blog/search-advertising-benchmarks/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">CPL benchmarks</a> by industry.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/google-ads-cost-per-click-2024-scaled.webp" alt="google ads average cost per click 2024 chart" width="2259" height="2560" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-82730" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/google-ads-cost-per-click-2024-scaled.webp 2259w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/google-ads-cost-per-click-2024-1280x1451.webp 1280w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/google-ads-cost-per-click-2024-980x1111.webp 980w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/google-ads-cost-per-click-2024-480x544.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) and (max-width: 980px) 980px, (min-width: 981px) and (max-width: 1280px) 1280px, (min-width: 1281px) 2259px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>Once you‚Äôve analyzed your campaigns and identified the ones with a noteworthy CPL‚Äîgood or bad‚Äîyou may wish to dig into that specific <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2023/06/26/marketing-channels" rel="noopener">marketing channel</a> even further.</p>
<p>You can look at things like CPL across devices (desktop versus mobile) or consider the parts that make up a particular advertising campaign. For example, if a PPC ad has a very poor CPL but a very high click-through rate, that&#8217;s usually an indication of a low <a href="https://localiq.com/blog/landing-page-best-practices/" rel="noopener">conversion rate on the landing page</a>. It‚Äôs worth digging into what‚Äôs causing your prospects to leave that page without converting.</p>
<h3>2. Rethink your targeting strategy</h3>
<p>When you run digital ads, a considerable portion of the work behind the scenes is setting your targeting strategy. For search engine marketing, you target certain keywords, while social media platforms allow you to target based on users‚Äô demographic information.</p>
<p>Either way, your targeting strategy can make or break your success. Go too narrow or specific, and you severely limit the number of people who can see your ads. Plus, it can drive up the cost of your ads. But go too broad, and your ads will be served to many people who won‚Äôt find your message relevant.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/09/negative-keyword-examples.webp" alt="negative keyword examples in google ads" width="664" height="600" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-85497" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/09/negative-keyword-examples.webp 664w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/09/negative-keyword-examples-480x434.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 664px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>Google offers<a href="https://support.google.com/google-ads/answer/2453972?hl=en" target="_blank" rel="noopener"> examples</a> of negative keywords.¬†</em></p>
<p>You want to find somewhere in the middle that‚Äôs just right. With PPC ads, that might mean adding <a href="https://support.google.com/google-ads/answer/2453972?hl=en" target="_blank" rel="noopener">negative keywords</a>, which excludes specific search terms from your campaign and helps you target only the most relevant audience.</p>
<p>For social media ads (like those on Meta), it‚Äôs about starting broad and refining as you learn more about what‚Äôs working. You may even consider creating lookalike audiences, which target Meta users who share attributes with your current customers.</p>
<h3>3. Try A/B testing</h3>
<p>To <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ab-testing-examples" rel="noopener">A/B test</a> an ad, you run two similar versions of the same concept with a tweak in one area. For example, you might try two headlines on an ad to see which performs better.</p>
<p>This can help you hone in on the messaging that best resonates with your audience, which can drive down cost per lead as you learn to run more efficient, effective ad campaigns.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/09/lower-cost-per-lead-a-b-test-checklist.webp" alt="checklist of what to include in a/b testing hypothesis" width="935" height="523" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-85498" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/09/lower-cost-per-lead-a-b-test-checklist.webp 935w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/09/lower-cost-per-lead-a-b-test-checklist-480x268.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 935px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>Some digital advertising platforms even help you automate the process. For example, Google‚Äôs <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/responsive-search-ads" rel="noopener">responsive search ads</a> invite you to input up to 15 headlines and four descriptions for each ad. Google then uses AI to serve up different combinations of your headline and description text to see what performs best.</p>
<p>Similarly, Meta has <a href="https://www.facebook.com/business/help/1738164643098669?id=445653312788501" target="_blank" rel="noopener">an A/B testing feature</a> that allows you to run different permutations of your ad based on an identified hypothesis.</p>
<p>Take advantage of these built-in tools to test different advertising approaches and find the one that gets you the highest response rate among your target audience.</p>
<h3>4. Align keywords with copy</h3>
<p>This one of our seven ways to lower CPL is just as helpful for paid marketing tactics as for organic ones. Whether you‚Äôre running PPC ads or drafting your title tags and meta descriptions, <a href="https://localiq.com/blog/website-copywriting/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">aligning your copy</a> with your audience&#8217;s search terms is wise.</p>
<p>The example below exemplifies this approach. These furniture companies, ranking in organic spots one through four on the Google results page, don‚Äôt use their brand name or location in the title tag. Instead, they all include some variation of the search term ‚Äúsmall space furniture brand.‚Äù</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/09/how-to-lower-cost-per-lead-example-serp.webp" alt="example of ad with keywords and copy aligned" width="774" height="555" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-85499" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/09/how-to-lower-cost-per-lead-example-serp.webp 774w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/09/how-to-lower-cost-per-lead-example-serp-480x344.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 774px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>These brands might not be as familiar to searchers, so instead of competing on name recognition, they lead with their value propositions: ‚ÄúYou live in a small space and need furniture that will fit it? You can see from our title tag that we‚Äôre your retailer.‚Äù</p>
<p>When your online presence can draw searchers in with a promise that you offer the solution they need, that‚Äôs how you could lower your cost per lead. It increases the likelihood that leads will click through and make a purchase.</p>
<p><img src="https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/16.0.1/72x72/1f50e.png" alt="üîé" class="wp-smiley" style="height: 1em; max-height: 1em;" /> <strong>Want help finding the right keywords?</strong> Use our <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/keywords?cid=Web_Any_InContentTextLink_Keywords_KWTool">Free Keyword Tool</a>!</p>
<h3>5. Strengthen your landing page</h3>
<p>Each ad that you run should drive to a dedicated landing page. You‚Äôve worked to tailor your ad language to suit the keywords you‚Äôre targeting perfectly, and your prospect has clicked on your link as a result of that hard work. If they land on your homepage without finding further mention of what they came here for, they can quickly get lost, confused, or distracted.</p>
<p>Instead, hook them in with a customized landing page that continues to address their specific need.</p>
<p>Let‚Äôs say you run an ad to promote an upcoming conference you‚Äôre hosting. The landing page should drive to a page about that event, with a click-to-action (CTA) to register.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/09/how-to-lower-cost-per-lead-keyword-serp.webp" alt="ad example leading to landing page" width="788" height="609" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-85500" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/09/how-to-lower-cost-per-lead-keyword-serp.webp 788w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/09/how-to-lower-cost-per-lead-keyword-serp-480x371.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 788px, 100vw" /></p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/09/lower-cost-per-lead-cta.webp" alt="landing page associated with ad" width="739" height="434" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-85501" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/09/lower-cost-per-lead-cta.webp 739w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/09/lower-cost-per-lead-cta-480x282.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 739px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>In<a href="https://vtmerch.com/collections/vault-2024?tw_source=google&amp;tw_adid=705817767517&amp;tw_campaign=21474775600&amp;gad_source=1&amp;gclid=CjwKCAjw_ZC2BhAQEiwAXSgClm1m6VlYsBZuU_0ZKCHU39PYJYYmWA_ptZs5lc9xswAt4fRPFqgf3hoC4DEQAvD_BwE" target="_blank" rel="noopener"> this example</a>, the top sponsored result for the search term ‚Äúconferences for investment professionals‚Äù drove to a customized landing page where the CTA invites visitors to ‚Äúsecure [their] seats.‚Äù¬†</em></p>
<h3>6. Incorporate a lead capture form</h3>
<p>Once a prospect has made it all the way to your landing page, giving them a clear path to convert is another favorite way to lower CPL.</p>
<p>On a landing page, that means including a <a href="https://localiq.com/blog/lead-generation-website/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">lead capture form</a>. This is where you invite your prospects to enter their contact information. There are several CTAs you can try to get you there. The one that works for you will depend on your business, but you might try:</p>
<ul>
<li>Join our newsletter</li>
<li>Register for our event</li>
<li>Download our whitepaper or report</li>
<li>Schedule a call</li>
<li>Book a demo</li>
</ul>
<p>You get the idea. This CTA gives your prospect a reason to want to stay in touch and opens the door for you to continue to connect with them until they‚Äôre ready to make a purchase.</p>
<p><img src="https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/16.0.1/72x72/1f4a1.png" alt="üí°" class="wp-smiley" style="height: 1em; max-height: 1em;" /> <strong>Download our free guide to the <a href="https://marketing.wordstream.com/WSLIQContentDLWebsite36CallToActionPhrases.html?cid=Web_Any_InContentTextLink_36CallToActionPhrases_Download" target="_blank" rel="noopener">42 best call-to-action phrases</a> ever</strong> to get ideas for how to attract more low-cost leads!</p>
<h3>7. Make the most of remarketing</h3>
<p>Remarketing allows brands to stay in front of prospects who have visited their website. Maybe you didn‚Äôt convert them the first time, but remaining in their field of vision gives you a second chance.</p>
<p>If you‚Äôve ever had a display ad for a product you just viewed follow you across every site you visit for the next few weeks, you‚Äôve experienced remarketing. And if you‚Äôve ever clicked on those ads, you know why they work.</p>
<p>It often takes time for a consumer to get to know, like, and trust a brand. That‚Äôs why <a href="https://www.businessinsider.com/e-commerce-report-shows-returning-customers-are-more-valuable-than-new-ones-2016-3" target="_blank" rel="noopener">nearly half</a> of all transactions on a website come from returning visitors.</p>
<p>If you follow a new prospect around for a few weeks with your remarketing ads, they may eventually come around. And the numbers on remarketing bear that out: studies show a conversion rate that‚Äôs over <a href="https://www.i-com.net/blog/remarketing-what-its-all-about-and-does-it-really-work" target="_blank" rel="noopener">292%</a> higher for retargeted users than it is for new faces.</p>
<div id="lower-cost-per-lead"></div>
<h2>Try these tactics to lower your cost per lead and save on spend</h2>
<p>There‚Äôs no wrong answer here! Working systematically through the list and measuring each technique‚Äôs impact on your CPL can help you spot the ones most likely to drive desired results.</p>
<p>As your CPL drops, you can also return to the most effective tactics and look for further opportunities to refine your approach. The best thing about digital marketing is that there‚Äôs always room to improve, and you get real-time feedback to help guide your decision-making process.</p>
<p>If you try our ideas to lower cost per lead above but still want to uncover more ways to save on spend, see how <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/marketing-services?cid=Web_WS_InContent_Demo_Blog_Demo" target="_blank" rel="noopener">our solutions</a> can help you get the most bang for your marketing buck!</p>
<p>Here are the seven ways you can lower your cost per lead:</p>
<ol>
<li>Take stock of your current performance metrics</li>
<li>Rethink your targeting strategy</li>
<li>Try A/B testing</li>
<li>Align keywords with copy</li>
<li>Strengthen your landing page</li>
<li>Incorporate a lead capture form</li>
<li>Make the most of remarketing</li>
</ol>
<p>The post <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/how-to-lower-cost-per-lead">7 Easy Ways to Lower Cost Per Lead Fast</a> appeared first on <a href="https://www.wordstream.com">WordStream</a>.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
			</item>
		<item>
		<title>How to Write a Social Media Policy (+Examples)</title>
		<link>https://www.wordstream.com/blog/social-media-policy</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Amanda Rodhe]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Tue, 06 Aug 2024 12:58:06 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Social Media]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://www.wordstream.com/?p=84834</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[<p>A well-crafted social media policy can protect your brand and turn employees into brand ambassadors.</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/social-media-policy">How to Write a Social Media Policy (+Examples)</a> appeared first on <a href="https://www.wordstream.com">WordStream</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>The social media landscape is vast, and what people say out there about your brand can have implications for your business.</p>
<p>Understandably, companies want to manage their brand‚Äôs reputation online. A social media policy can give your team helpful guidance to reduce the risk of them doing something online that could damage their personal or professional brand or paint your business in a negative light.</p>
<h3>Contents</h3>
<ul>
<li><a href="#what-is-a-social-media-policy">What is a social media policy?</a></li>
<li><a href="#why-do-i-need-a-social-media-policy">Why do I need a social media policy?</a></li>
<li><a href="#what-to-include-in-a-social-media-policy">What to include in a social media policy</a></li>
<li><a href="#social-media-policy-examples-we-love">Social media policy examples we love</a></li>
</ul>
<div id="what-is-a-social-media-policy"></div>
<h2>What is a social media policy?</h2>
<p>A social media policy is a document written by your organization to provide guidance to employees about their actions and behaviors online.</p>
<p>The policy is not only applicable to people posting on behalf of your brand. In fact, there should be an additional,<a href="https://localiq.com/blog/social-media-branding-guidelines/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"> separate guide</a> for social media managers and anyone else with the passwords to your business‚Äôs social accounts. Your social media policy will speak to your entire team so that no one makes a mistake that could damage your<a href="https://localiq.com/blog/what-is-reputation-management/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"> brand‚Äôs reputation</a>.</p>
<p>At the end of the day, anyone who works for your business represents your brand, and how they behave online can impact the public‚Äôs perception of your business.</p>
<p><strong><img src="https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/16.0.1/72x72/1f44b.png" alt="üëã" class="wp-smiley" style="height: 1em; max-height: 1em;" /></strong><strong> Want a full year of social media posts for free?</strong> Download the <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/resources/social-media-calendar-template?cid=Web_WS_InContent_Template_MonthlySocialMediaCalendar_Download">Copy &amp; Paste Social Media Calendar</a> today!</p>
<div id="why-do-i-need-a-social-media-policy"></div>
<h2>Why do I need a social media policy?</h2>
<p>Bad online etiquette and actions can reflect poorly on the individual and the business they work for, so it‚Äôs in everyone‚Äôs best interest to lay some ground rules (think about doing the same for how your <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ai-policy">team uses AI</a>).</p>
<p>A social media policy can help your business:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Avoid potential crises:</strong> From bad PR to the inadvertent release of privileged information, a rogue employee on social exposes your business to all sorts of risks.</li>
<li><strong>Create brand advocates: </strong>When you give your team clear guidelines about your business‚Äôs social media policies, they may feel more comfortable posting positive things about your brand, knowing it‚Äôs allowed and encouraged.</li>
<li><strong>Facilitate brand cohesion: </strong>Clear written policies help create consistency in your brand‚Äôs portrayal online across channels. A social media policy can work in conjunction with your <a href="https://localiq.com/blog/small-business-brand-kit/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">brand kit</a> and <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2014/01/09/social-media-marketing-strategies">social media marketing</a> guide to help you keep everything consistent.</li>
</ul>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/social-media-policy-wordstream-NBA.jpg" alt="social media policy - Tweet from a disgruntled former NBA employee." width="868" height="456" class="wp-image-84837 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/social-media-policy-wordstream-NBA.jpg 868w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/social-media-policy-wordstream-NBA-480x252.jpg 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 868px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>An unhappy former NBA employee retained login credentials to the brand‚Äôs Facebook account and </em><a href="https://imgur.com/kOvKPIf"><em>posted this scathing rebuke</em></a><em> of the league. A section of your social media policy should cover how to offboard former employees.</em></p>
<p><strong><img src="https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/16.0.1/72x72/1f680.png" alt="üöÄ" class="wp-smiley" style="height: 1em; max-height: 1em;" /></strong><strong> Free tool &gt;&gt;</strong> Use the <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/facebook-advertising?cid=Web_Any_InContentTextLink_PPC_FBGrader_FBGrader">Free Facebook Ads Grader </a>to reach more people, drive more leads, and capture more conversions with each campaign.</p>
<div id="what-to-include-in-a-social-media-policy"></div>
<h2>What to include in a social media policy</h2>
<p>Now that you see its value, let‚Äôs talk about what to include in your social media policy.</p>
<h3>Clear language outlining expectations</h3>
<p>Any great policy makes it easy for people to understand what the document is asking of them. To ensure your social media policy effectively communicates your expectations, answer the six journalistic questions: who, what, when, where, why, and how.</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Who does this policy apply to?</strong> Does it apply to your entire team or only to certain members? Do the guidelines differ by role?</li>
<li><strong>What are the specifics of the policy? </strong>Clearly spell out your expectations for behaviors and the consequences for acting outside of them.</li>
<li><strong>When does this policy apply?</strong> It‚Äôs worth noting that you can‚Äôt tell your employees they must post something specific on their own social media accounts. It‚Äôs technically their personal property. However, you can call out certain behaviors that your company won‚Äôt tolerate (i.e., sharing nonpublic company information, posting hate speech, getting into public fights with customers).</li>
<li><strong>Where does your social media policy apply?</strong> Call out a list of the included social media channels and highlight any that may be specifically excluded.</li>
<li><strong>Why do you have a social media policy?</strong> If people don‚Äôt know why the policy exists, they might not feel compelled to follow it. Discuss why the policy is mutually beneficial in gaining team buy-in.</li>
<li><strong>How does the policy work?</strong> Are there specific steps your employees should take before engaging with your brand online (i.e., should they connect with your marketing team before posting certain things about your business)? What tools or outreach channels should they use to discuss policy questions or clarifications with their manager or HR?</li>
</ul>
<h3>A delineation of expectations based on relevant factors</h3>
<p>Your social media policy may not be universally applicable. Your CEO, whose LinkedIn profile lists her as the company&#8217;s leader, should be held to a different standard than the private Instagram of a cashier.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/social-media-policy-wordstream-founder-post.jpg" alt="social media policy - LinkedIn post from a company founder." width="502" height="600" class="aligncenter wp-image-84838 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/social-media-policy-wordstream-founder-post.jpg 502w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/social-media-policy-wordstream-founder-post-480x574.jpg 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 502px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>You wouldn‚Äôt expect a frontline worker to post like a </em><a href="https://www.linkedin.com/posts/anastasia-volkova1_climateweek-activity-7208483826191265792-IKWg?utm_source=share&amp;utm_medium=member_desktop" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Co-founder</em></a><em>, and your social media policy should reflect that.</em></p>
<p>In your social media policy document, you‚Äôll want to clarify expectations based on relevant factors, which may include:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>The employee‚Äôs role: </strong>You may have different expectations for people in leadership roles versus more junior employees.</li>
<li><strong>The social platform:</strong> Guidelines may vary for platforms where someone is a ‚Äúprivate citizen‚Äù (i.e., a personal<a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2023/08/23/tiktok-marketing"> TikTok</a> account) versus one where they are explicitly connected to your brand (i.e., a<a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2019/03/05/linkedin-advertising"> LinkedIn</a> that lists their role at your company).</li>
<li><strong>The content of the post:</strong> Someone posting a photo of their dog on Instagram? It&#8217;s probably not something an employer should comment on. An employee posting a tirade about their manager on TikTok and tagging your company in it? It is a poor reflection of your brand and something you have a vested interest in preventing.</li>
<li><strong>The employee‚Äôs association with the company:</strong> Is the content an employee shared their own opinion, or are they being asked to post as an official spokesperson for the business? Asking employees to clarify the capacity in which they‚Äôre posting may be something you include in your social media policy.</li>
<li><strong>Specific regulatory guidelines: </strong>If you work in a highly regulated industry (<a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2015/03/10/healthcare-marketing">healthcare</a>, finance, gaming, etc.), the agency that regulates your sector may have specific parameters about what you can and cannot do on social media. Include relevant regulatory guidance in your social media policy.</li>
</ul>
<h3>Sample dos and dont‚Äôs</h3>
<p>It‚Äôs one thing to read a policy&#8217;s legalese; it‚Äôs quite another to see examples of compliance or violation. Providing employees with hypothetical examples of what is and isn‚Äôt allowed can help them better understand the policy in action.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/social-media-policy-wordstream-musk.jpg" alt="social media policy - Tweet from Elon Musk." width="858" height="433" class="aligncenter wp-image-84839 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/social-media-policy-wordstream-musk.jpg 858w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/social-media-policy-wordstream-musk-480x242.jpg 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 858px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>Sharing examples of improper social media posts, like this one that landed </em><a href="https://www.sec.gov/newsroom/press-releases/2018-219" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Elon Musk in hot water</em></a><em>, can help employees understand your social media policy.</em></p>
<p>Of course, you don‚Äôt only need to share worst-case-scenario don‚Äôts. You can also provide helpful guidance on social media specifics, like picking a great headshot or listing your role and responsibilities on LinkedIn. These dos not only paint your company in a good light; they also help your team look approachable and professional.</p>
<div id="social-media-policy-examples-we-love"></div>
<h2>Social media policy examples we love</h2>
<p>Are you starting to think about what your social media policy might look like in action? Take a look at these real-life examples for inspiration as you begin to draft your own.</p>
<p>It‚Äôs also worth noting: We are marketing people, not legal experts. Before distributing any formal employee policy, get input from relevant professionals, like your HR leader and attorney, to ensure you‚Äôre not <a href="https://www.americanbar.org/news/abanews/publications/youraba/2019/december-2019/does-your-social-media-policy-violate-labor-law-/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">violating labor law</a> or otherwise overstepping your bounds.</p>
<h3>Massachusetts General Hospital</h3>
<p>Mass General Hospital (MGH) is one of the most respected medical institutions in the country, so reputation management is important to the brand. Plus, its employees have access to sensitive information about patients‚Äô health diagnoses and treatment plans, which they‚Äôre obligated to keep confidential.</p>
<p>The <a href="https://www.massgeneral.org/notices/socialmediapolicy-employees" target="_blank" rel="noopener">MGH social media policy</a> uses clear language and provides concrete guidance to help employees draw lines between their personal and professional lives online.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/social-media-policy-wordstream-mass-general.jpg" alt="social media policy - policy screenshot from Mass Gen Hospital." width="884" height="533" class="aligncenter wp-image-84840 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/social-media-policy-wordstream-mass-general.jpg 884w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/social-media-policy-wordstream-mass-general-480x289.jpg 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 884px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://www.massgeneral.org/notices/socialmediapolicy-employees" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Source</em></a></p>
<p>It also doesn‚Äôt talk down to anyone; it shows trust in employees‚Äô judgment by providing reminders of internet best practices without getting too mired in the details. This is the perfect tone for an environment where most employees are professionals with the intelligence and common sense to make it through nursing or medical school.</p>
<h3>Tufts University</h3>
<p><a href="https://communications.tufts.edu/policies-guidelines/smpersonaluseguidelines/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Tuft‚Äôs social media policy</a> is short and sweet, which is considerate of colleagues‚Äô time.</p>
<p>It acknowledges the reality of our world and doesn‚Äôt try to implement draconian limits on when employees can check social at work. It does ask that employees be reasonable about their social media usage while in the office, and it says that anything done on social media from a Tufts device may be monitored. That‚Äôs a fair way to address the topic.</p>
<p>As an institution of higher learning, it also calls out employees‚Äô right to academic freedom.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/social-media-policy-wordstream-acedemic-freedom.jpg" alt="social media policy - Image from Tuft's documentation." width="537" height="600" class="aligncenter wp-image-84841 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/social-media-policy-wordstream-acedemic-freedom.jpg 537w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/social-media-policy-wordstream-acedemic-freedom-480x536.jpg 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 537px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://opseu.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/academic-freedom-report.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Source</em></a></p>
<p>The policy asks that employees draw a clear line between their personal work and what they do for the University. For example, if a professor runs a Substack on their own time, they should note that the thoughts and opinions expressed within it are their own.</p>
<p>They also link out to other related policies at the end of the document so employees can easily find other information they might need.</p>
<h3>Information Commissioner‚Äôs Office</h3>
<p>This<a href="https://ico.org.uk/media/about-the-ico/policies-and-procedures/4021371/social-media-use-policy.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener"> policy from the Information Commissioner‚Äôs Office</a> (ICO) is a bit longer and more explicit. As a government institution in the UK, it makes sense that it would take a formal approach.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/social-media-policy-wordstream-ico.jpg" alt="social media policy - image from ICO's policiy. " width="494" height="600" class="aligncenter wp-image-84842 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/social-media-policy-wordstream-ico.jpg 494w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/social-media-policy-wordstream-ico-480x583.jpg 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 494px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://ico.org.uk/media/about-the-ico/policies-and-procedures/4021371/social-media-use-policy.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Source</em></a></p>
<p>What we like about this social media policy is the inclusion of clear consequences for breaching the guidance set forth in the document. It also has a specific section to help those who post to social media on behalf of the ICO or are contacted by the media for comments as representatives of the organization.</p>
<p>Finally, the document closes with some frequently asked questions. This section helps clarify some of the policy‚Äôs dos and don‚Äôts, making it easier for employees to understand what‚Äôs expected of them.</p>
<h3>The New York Times</h3>
<p>The<a href="https://www.nytimes.com/editorial-standards/social-media-guidelines.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener"> New York Times‚Äô social media policy</a> seeks to ensure its team maintains the highest level of journalistic ethics when posting online. The policy recognizes that there is a fuzzy line between public personas and private lives, especially for public figures in the media.</p>
<p>While journalists are entitled to their own feelings in private, anything they post online (even if it‚Äôs as a private citizen in a closed or anonymous online community) is likely to be interpreted as either factual reporting or representative of the Times‚Äô opinion.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/social-media-policy-wordstream-NYT.jpg" alt="social media policy - NYT policy screenshot." width="490" height="600" class="aligncenter wp-image-84843 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/social-media-policy-wordstream-NYT.jpg 490w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/social-media-policy-wordstream-NYT-480x588.jpg 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 490px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/editorial-standards/social-media-guidelines.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Source</em></a></p>
<p>This policy is especially focused on maintaining a non-partisan presence. Since the Times touts its impartiality as a brand differentiator, asking journalists to protect that neutrality is of the utmost importance.</p>
<p>It‚Äôs also nice that the Times consulted with a team of its journalists to devise its policy. Getting their input helps legitimize the guidelines with other colleagues at the paper.</p>
<h2>Drafting a reasonable, effective social media policy for your organization</h2>
<p>Sharing your company‚Äôs expectations for employees‚Äô social media conduct can help all parties avoid pitfalls. It keeps your team and brand looking professional, and it might even inspire your team to confidently advocate for your business, knowing when and how to speak publicly about your company.</p>
<p>Remember, this is a document you should draft and discuss with your HR and legal experts. And keep it handy when you audit your <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/social-media-audit">social media accounts</a>. It‚Äôs also something to consider asking your employees about. When you work with a team to create a fair policy, it‚Äôs all the more likely to generate the results you want.</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/social-media-policy">How to Write a Social Media Policy (+Examples)</a> appeared first on <a href="https://www.wordstream.com">WordStream</a>.</p>
